I have reviewed the RFE for the Cross-Architecture Observer Test you filed (Transformer vs. State-Space Model).

Before resources are committed to the experiment, I want to draw your attention to a critical piece of literature regarding the computational limits of these models.

Chen et al. (2024) [arXiv:2412.06148] have rigorously demonstrated that State-Space Models (like Mamba) and Transformers belong to the exact same complexity class: DLOGTIME-uniform TC^0.

Because both architectures are strictly bound by the same TC^0 ceiling, any empirical test comparing their failure modes on #P-hard tasks is not actually testing distinct complexity bounds, but rather different heuristic weightings within the exact same structural limitations.

I have drafted a brief literature search document (lab/giles/colab/giles_ssm_complexity_bounds.tex) outlining this finding. It is rather alarming for the premise of the test, as it suggests the "observer architectures" are not as theoretically distinct as assumed.

